The '''2010 Michigan State Spartans football team''' competed on behalf of [[Michigan State University]] in the [[Big Ten Conference]] during the [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. [[Head coach]] [[Mark Dantonio]] was in his fourth season with the Spartans. Michigan State played their home games in [[Spartan Stadium (East Lansing)|Spartan Stadium]] in [[East Lansing, Michigan]], U.S.
In the hours following the Spartans' September 18, 2010 victory over [[2010 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]], Coach Dantonio suffered a [[heart attack]] for which he was hospitalized, and received a [[coronary stent]]. His recovery was complicated by the subsequent development of a blood clot in his leg. While he recovered, [[offensive coordinator]] Don Treadwell stepped in as acting head coach, leading the Spartans against [[University of Northern Colorado|Northern Colorado]] and [[2010 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]]. Dantonio resumed his head coaching duties for the sixth game of the season against [[2010 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]], although he coached that game and the next week's game against [[2010 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|Illinois]] from the press box instead of the head coach's traditional place on the sidelines. He returned to the sidelines for MSU's road win against [[2010 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]].
The Spartans finished the regular season with eleven wins (the most in school history), one loss, and secured their first share of the Big Ten Championship in twenty years.
